    "created_at": "2015-09-29T15:42:37Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-09-29T15:42:37Z",
    "body": "As @bluss mentioned, `catch_panic` is probably what you want for now as it's just a direct wrapper around `try`. The main difference is that `catch_panic` has the bounds of `Send + 'static` on the closure, which is a topic of hot debate over on the RFC!\n\nIf you'd like to get the same functionality as before, you can build the old `try` on top of `catch_panic`:\n\n``` rust\n#![feature(catch_panic)]\n\nuse std::thread;\n\npub unsafe fn try<R, F: FnOnce() -> R>(f: F) -> thread::Result<R> {\n    let mut f = Some(f);\n    let f = &mut f as *mut Option<F> as usize;\n    thread::catch_panic(move || {\n        (*(f as *mut Option<F>)).take().unwrap()()\n    })\n}\n```\n",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
